**Treatment Principles:**

**General Approach:**
1. Correct identifiable causes
2. Improve natural fertility
3. Assisted reproduction if needed
| Consider age and time constraints

**Lifestyle Modifications:**

**Weight Management:**
- Underweight: Gain to normal BMI
| Overweight/obese: 5-10% weight loss can improve ovulation

**Other Changes:**
| Smoking cessation |
| Limit alcohol |
| Reduce caffeine |
| Exercise moderation |
| Stress reduction |

**Ovulation Induction:**

**Clomiphene Citrate:**

**Mechanism:**
| Estrogen receptor modulator |
| Increases GnRH, FSH, LH |
| Stimulates follicular development |

**Indications:**
| PCOS |
| Unexplained infertility |
| Hypothal-pituitary dysfunction

**Protocol:**
| Days 5-9 of cycle (or 3-7) |
| Start 50 mg, increase to 100-150 mg |
| Monitor with ultrasound (if multiple follicles)

**Risks:**
| Multiple pregnancy (5-10%) |
| Ovarian hyperstimulation (rare) |
| Hot flashes, mood changes |

**Letrozole:**

**Mechanism:**
| Aromatase inhibitor |
| Reduces estrogen conversion |
| Increases FSH secretion

**Advantages:**
| Lower multiple pregnancy rate than clomiphene |
| Better for PCOS
| Fewer side effects

**Gonadotropins:**

**Medications:**
| FSH alone (Follistim, Gonal-F) |
| FSH + LH (Menopur) |
| hCG trigger (Ovidrel)

**Protocol:**
| Injectable |
| Strict monitoring required |
| Can cause multiple ovulation
| Higher multiple pregnancy risk (20-30%)

**Surgical Treatments:**

**Myomectomy:**
| Remove fibroids |
| Improves fertility if cavity distorted |

**Ovarian Drilling:|
| Laparoscopic treatment for PCOS |
| Reduces androgen production |
| Consider after failed ovulation induction

**Tubal Surgery:|
| Adhesiolysis |
| Salpingostomy (for hydrosalpinx) |
